I&#39;m thinking that we could use the int return value to find the length of the string.

For our base case, a string that is just the null terminator `&#39;\0&#39;` will always be zero.
```C++
if (*c == &#39;\0&#39;) {
    return 0;
}
```

Starting from `&quot;abcde&quot;`, which has a null terminator appended at the end, we can&#39;t know for sure when the string will end. So we figure that the length of the string will always be 1 greater than the pointer, advanced one step ahead, which will make the char * point to `&quot;bcde&quot;`, as so on.
```C++
return 1 + StringReverse(c + 1);
```
And that&#39;s pretty much it for the recursive function. 
```C++
int StringReverse(char *c) {
    if (*c == &#39;\0&#39;) {
        return 0;
    }
    return 1 + StringReverse(c + 1);
}
```
Now this won&#39;t do anything on its own, the inner calls of the function won&#39;t know where the beginning of the string is to allow for swapping... except for the place that initially called it.

So we wrap the recursive function call with another function that performs the swapping.
```C++
void ReverseString(char *start) {
    int size = StringReverse(start);

